limitation of retrospective research in general is related to the accuracy and	144.6999969482422	277.97967529296875	11.0	366.86109924316406	181
reliability of the information provided by the participants. HARRISON et al. (2011)	144.6999969482422	292.0797119140625	11.0	395.3511505126953	181
propose that "we have no way of evaluating to what extent the memories	144.6999969482422	306.2796630859375	11.0	354.31004333496094	181
approximated a true rendering of the experiences of these participants" (p.223).	144.6999969482422	320.37969970703125	11.0	388.24525451660156	181
RICHARDSON et al. (2009) have also commented on this debate between	144.6999969482422	334.5796813964844	11.0	363.85816955566406	181
realism and constructionism and has argued for a middle-ground or pragmatic	144.6999969482422	348.6796875	11.0	380.0830841064453	181
perspective. RICHARDSON et al. (ibid.) suggest that recall and reconstruction	144.6999969482422	362.87969970703125	11.0	380.87513732910156	181
are interrelated concepts and that in qualitative research, the accuracy of the	144.6999969482422	376.97967529296875	11.0	374.51722717285156	181
recalled information is less important than meaning and experience. In our study	144.6999969482422	391.1796875	11.0	391.4572296142578	181
we were not only interested in when life events occurred, but also the subjective	144.6999969482422	405.2796936035156	11.0	388.98207092285156	181
experiences and meanings of these life events, and how these events influenced	144.6999969482422	419.47967529296875	11.0	393.7012481689453	181
and changed the lives of the participants. Given our focus on experiences (and	144.6999969482422	433.5796813964844	11.0	384.14222717285156	181
with concerns pertaining to recall in the back of our minds) we decided to	144.6999969482422	447.7796936035156	11.0	355.8610076904297	181
interview the mothers and adolescents while the adolescent was completing	144.6999969482422	461.87969970703125	11.0	369.6660919189453	181
his/her treatment at the rehabilitation centers. It is our experience that this	144.6999969482422	476.0796813964844	11.0	359.7330780029297	181
facilitated recall as the participants were reflecting on current and fairly recent	144.6999969482422	490.1796875	11.0	377.93812561035156	181
experiences. [29]	144.6999969482422	504.37969970703125	11.0	83.94700622558594	181
Furthermore researching sensitive issues, like those discussed in our study, is a	144.6999969482422	532.6796875	11.0	390.09303283691406	182
challenging task which required us to identify methodologies that are	144.6999969482422	546.7796630859375	11.0	334.5210723876953	182
appropriately sensitive while at the same time facilitative. Using the literature as	144.6999969482422	560.9796752929688	11.0	387.25502014160156	182
our guide (see for example BUTLER & BAULD, 2005; USHER et al., 2007), we	144.6999969482422	575.0797119140625	11.000015258789062	385.0219268798828	182
understood that talking about the adolescent's substance abuse would be a	144.6999969482422	589.2797241210938	11.0	367.89515686035156	182
difficult task for both the mothers and the adolescents (especially to a "stranger").	144.6999969482422	603.3796997070312	11.0	396.9462432861328	182
In this regard, we were cognizant of the possibility of selective recall where	144.6999969482422	617.5797119140625	11.0	363.89100646972656	182
participants are unable (or perhaps unwilling) to recall certain events, or show	144.6999969482422	631.6796875	11.0	378.21302795410156	182
selective recall bias in favor of what is "easier" to discuss. Studies show that	144.6999969482422	645.8796997070312	11.0	370.66712951660156	182
individuals have the tendency to forget information that they perceive self-	144.6999969482422	659.979736328125	11.0	359.98609924316406	182
threatening (for full discussions on these issues, please refer to GREEN,	144.6999969482422	674.1796875	11.0	354.3319854736328	182
SEDIKIDES & GREGG, 2007; SAUNDERS, 2012). We therefore recognized that	144.6999969482422	688.2797241210938	11.0	394.83412170410156	182
participant recall, which was essential to obtain data that is information rich in our	144.6999969482422	702.479736328125	11.0	395.3952178955078	182
study, was intrinsically dependent on our participants' abilities and willingness to	144.6999969482422	716.5797119140625	11.000007629394531	389.54310607910156	182
tell their stories. As put forth by BROWN and REAVY (2014) recall operates as a	144.6999969482422	730.7797241210938	11.000007629394531	393.7450714111328	182
shared activity and in our study the LG acted as a quasi-neutral stimulus to the	144.6999969482422	744.8796997070312	11.0	383.4712677001953	182
participants memories that accommodated the complexities of recall and	144.6999969482422	759.0797119140625	11.000007629394531	353.3970489501953	182
